WEBVTT

00:00.962 --> 00:04.125
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.686 --> 00:18.380
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.121 --> 00:26.649
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.709 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.982
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:40.649 --> 00:41.290
Peace be with you.

00:41.330 --> 00:43.133
Friends, we come to New Year's Day.

00:43.213 --> 00:48.621
We have the New Year celebration of the liturgical year, the first Sunday of Advent.

00:49.342 --> 00:55.251
A day of great importance as we once again commence our march through the liturgical year.

00:55.311 --> 00:57.234
And here's the thing I want you to see.

00:57.378 --> 01:00.924
Advent is the season of sacred waiting.

01:02.226 --> 01:05.471
We're waiting for the Adventus, for the coming of the Savior.

01:06.112 --> 01:13.443
It's four weeks of looking and waiting and hoping, watching with a kind of joyful anticipation.

01:14.205 --> 01:15.006
And I want you to see this.

01:15.427 --> 01:22.858
In a way, Advent, even though it's just four weeks, name something true of all of life, at least life in this world.

01:24.200 --> 01:25.202
All of us know

01:26.242 --> 01:30.067
There's a happiness that we want, but we don't have.

01:31.008 --> 01:32.069
I don't mean we're all in despair.

01:32.109 --> 01:34.372
I mean, we're making our way through life and there's all kinds of good things.

01:34.432 --> 01:40.400
But deep down, we know that we're hungry for something that we don't have.

01:42.002 --> 01:51.634
And even at the best moments, I might say, especially at the best moments of life, we come to realize that, you know, you've attained the thing you wanted forever.

01:52.098 --> 01:55.842
You've reached this great goal of your life and you say, wonderful, wonderful.

01:55.862 --> 01:59.666
And then the next day it's like, okay, now what?

02:00.507 --> 02:01.808
Now what's my next goal?

02:02.469 --> 02:05.752
Because we know what we're hungry and thirsty for.

02:07.354 --> 02:08.876
We're not going to get in this world.

02:10.197 --> 02:17.525
Therefore there's a watching and waiting and hoping quality to all of life.

02:17.545 --> 02:18.866
Now put it very negatively.

02:19.426 --> 02:23.952
I've quoted before from Teresa Vavila that this life is like a bad night in a bad hotel.

02:24.353 --> 02:31.542
Now, again, that's putting it rather negatively, but you get the point that this is not what we're meant for, ultimately.

02:32.624 --> 02:36.449
A hotel is a place you go and you, okay, you spend a night because you're gonna go somewhere else.

02:36.489 --> 02:40.094
It's not home, but it's a provisional thing.

02:40.715 --> 02:43.939
Well, all of life is like that.

02:43.979 --> 02:49.266
Even the best life, the best moments is kind of like a bad night in a bad hotel.

02:49.378 --> 02:53.002
I'm still on my way somewhere else.

02:54.004 --> 02:58.289
And that's why I'm going to call it a spirituality of waiting.

02:59.671 --> 03:02.374
We'll mark the whole of one's life.

03:03.575 --> 03:03.876
Okay.

03:04.777 --> 03:05.698
But here's the problem.

03:06.299 --> 03:10.163
And I don't know if you're like me, but I'm not a patient person.

03:10.724 --> 03:13.327
Patience is not one of my virtues.

03:13.968 --> 03:15.730
I rather hate to wait.

03:16.354 --> 03:17.856
waiting for the time I was a little kid.

03:17.876 --> 03:21.941
I remember waiting for my mother to come pick me up after school when I was in fourth grade.

03:23.443 --> 03:26.547
Difficult, anxiety-producing, uneasy.

03:26.587 --> 03:32.675
I'm looking at these cars and all of a sudden, where is she supposed to be here right now?

03:33.856 --> 03:36.880
Other people getting picked up, well, they're getting it right.

03:37.020 --> 03:37.661
Where's my right?

03:38.602 --> 03:39.604
I've always hated waiting.

03:40.385 --> 03:41.586
I'll tell you very recently,

03:42.306 --> 03:48.214
I went to the eye doctor, and you know, when you go to the doctor, well, there's always a waiting room, first of all.

03:48.915 --> 03:51.138
And I was in that waiting room, probably 20 minutes.

03:51.418 --> 03:55.404
I got there right on time for the appointment, but, you know, 20 minutes, then my name is Cole.

03:55.524 --> 03:56.065
Okay, good.

03:56.405 --> 04:08.882
And I go to an office, I wait for a while longer, and then finally, it comes at one of the assistants to the doctor, and he takes me through a number of these, you know, tests from my eyes, and one, two, one, two.

04:09.058 --> 04:12.323
Okay, I do all that, and it's been a pretty thorough test.

04:12.944 --> 04:15.629
Then he says, well, now I'm going to put the drops in your eyes.

04:15.749 --> 04:16.410
I'm like, oh, really?

04:16.430 --> 04:17.632
You need the drops in your eyes?

04:17.652 --> 04:17.993
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

04:18.013 --> 04:19.074
The doctor, yeah, I need that.

04:19.695 --> 04:20.597
So I know the drill.

04:20.657 --> 04:22.099
They put the drops in your eyes.

04:22.119 --> 04:25.044
Then you have to wait because they have to take effect.

04:25.425 --> 04:28.690
So again, they send you out into the waiting room.

04:29.090 --> 04:35.697
And you know, there I sat, and you know, when these drops are dilating your pupils, so then you can't see properly.

04:36.238 --> 04:39.802
So you can't read, you can't look at your phone, you're just kind of sitting there.

04:40.643 --> 04:45.248
And 20 minutes, 30 minutes, 40 minutes.

04:45.628 --> 04:58.162
When it got to 50 minutes, I remember, I was so frustrated, and I went to see someone at the desk, and I said, you know, I've been here for like an hour and 15 minutes, I've been waiting here for 50 minutes,

04:58.434 --> 04:59.335
You know, what gives?

04:59.375 --> 05:02.498
And she goes, oh no, you're the next one, don't worry.

05:03.279 --> 05:06.142
So all right, another five minutes and then my name was called.

05:06.562 --> 05:11.928
And so I was brought down another hallway to not the first office to another office.

05:11.948 --> 05:13.550
And I was told, now sit there.

05:15.031 --> 05:19.536
Once again, I wait for the doctor and the door is closed.

05:20.216 --> 05:22.919
And so I can hear him out in the hallway.

05:22.999 --> 05:23.680
I can hear his voice.

05:23.720 --> 05:24.321
Oh, always come.

05:24.581 --> 05:25.682
No, he's coming to the next room.

05:25.986 --> 05:27.187
Oh, I hear him again.

05:27.748 --> 05:28.489
No, he was killing.

05:29.630 --> 05:34.797
I waited maybe another 20, 25 minutes before finally the doctor came in.

05:34.857 --> 05:35.658
And what did he say?

05:35.678 --> 05:37.159
Yeah, all looks good.

05:37.280 --> 05:44.028
I think that the prescription that they came up with like an hour and 15 minutes ago, that'll be fine and he signs off on it.

05:45.269 --> 05:52.798
My whole time there, two hours and 20 minutes probably, most of it waiting.

05:55.041 --> 05:55.922
I hate to wait.

05:56.322 --> 05:57.404
I hate to wait.

05:58.145 --> 06:10.684
F. Scott Fitzgerald said the three worst things in life are to try to please and not be able to lie in bed and not to sleep and to wait for someone who does not come.

06:13.548 --> 06:14.009
Pretty good.

06:14.770 --> 06:15.231
Pretty good.

06:15.512 --> 06:16.253
I hate to wait.

06:16.934 --> 06:20.900
But waiting is all over the Bible.

06:22.462 --> 06:24.946
The people of Israel have to wait.

06:25.762 --> 06:33.814
for centuries for the coming of the Messiah, generation after generation, leading, watching.

06:34.415 --> 06:43.087
Israel waits 400 years in slavery in Egypt before the deliverer comes.

06:44.449 --> 06:53.202
Abraham is promised a son who will carry on his name and make him the father of many nations.

06:53.858 --> 06:57.402
75, he's 85, he's 95.

06:57.982 --> 07:05.431
His wife is the same age and he has to wait until Isaac comes.

07:06.872 --> 07:15.201
Noah, remember when the ark lands on Mount Ararat and then he still has to wait until the water subsides.

07:15.261 --> 07:16.022
It's all eager.

07:16.042 --> 07:21.328
They give me at the eye doctor, but they were so eager to get out of that darn boat.

07:22.529 --> 07:23.410
But they had to

07:23.522 --> 07:24.123
Wait.

07:24.923 --> 07:31.830
Look how prominent waiting is in the spiritual tradition in the monastic life, keeping vigil.

07:32.731 --> 07:37.756
What's keeping vigil, but it's expectant, hopeful waiting.

07:38.216 --> 07:41.319
It's kind of a fancy liturgical word for waiting.

07:42.120 --> 07:52.210
Think of, you know, when you came to a monastery, still true to this day in its own way, but especially in the Middle Ages, you came and you petitioned, but then you were made to wait very often.

07:52.898 --> 07:56.163
you're being tested is this person really up to this life, you know?

07:56.604 --> 07:58.106
Are they coming here for the right reasons?

07:58.126 --> 07:59.408
We better test them.

08:01.191 --> 08:04.997
I love in Dante, the Divine Comedy.

08:06.700 --> 08:17.837
Sometimes as Virgil is leading Dante through hell, they're moving along and Virgil knows just where to go, but at a certain point, they're blocked and they just have to wait.

08:18.037 --> 08:19.840
And Dante says to Virgil, what's the matter?

08:19.880 --> 08:21.042
Can't you get us,

08:22.466 --> 08:25.829
We just have to wait for divine help to come.

08:25.849 --> 08:28.712
And eventually an angel comes and they make their way.

08:29.252 --> 08:31.415
Also at the very beginning of the purgatorial.

08:32.055 --> 08:36.740
So they're about to climb up Mount Purgatory, which is its own form of waiting, isn't it?

08:36.760 --> 08:40.103
They have to wait through all the disciplines of Mount Purgatory.

08:40.483 --> 08:48.491
But even before they get up on the mountain, they notice this whole group of people at the foot of Mount Purgatory, what are they doing?

08:49.652 --> 08:49.992
Nothing.

08:51.273 --> 08:51.954
They're waiting.

08:52.514 --> 08:54.817
they're waiting until they get permission to go up the mountain.

08:55.378 --> 08:57.521
It's like being in the doctor's office here.

08:57.541 --> 08:58.502
You're just waiting.

08:58.542 --> 09:01.025
All right, all right.

09:01.266 --> 09:02.828
So I hate waiting.

09:02.868 --> 09:08.495
I bet you hate waiting, but the Bible is telling us a lot about waiting.

09:09.176 --> 09:10.878
So what is going on?

09:12.040 --> 09:13.121
Here's how I put it, everybody.

09:13.141 --> 09:17.006
And this is now my advent thought for you the next four weeks.

09:18.248 --> 09:19.730
At the heart of it is,

09:21.314 --> 09:24.479
The painful process of decentering the ego.

09:26.402 --> 09:26.862
The ego.

09:26.882 --> 09:28.685
I want.

09:29.587 --> 09:30.468
I envision.

09:31.189 --> 09:32.190
I've got a plan.

09:32.251 --> 09:33.673
I've got a project.

09:34.294 --> 09:35.716
It's on my timetable.

09:35.816 --> 09:36.737
Let's get going.

09:36.858 --> 09:37.238
Come on.

09:37.318 --> 09:38.320
I know what I want to do.

09:39.381 --> 09:41.044
Yeah, that's most of us.

09:42.546 --> 09:47.253
But the spiritual life is about letting go of that ego.

09:47.293 --> 09:50.418
Decentering that ego.

09:51.074 --> 09:55.280
and allowing God to be the Lord of my life.

09:57.223 --> 10:03.111
Not to undertake my project all the time, but to wait on the Lord.

10:04.493 --> 10:05.675
Painful, uh-huh.

10:07.438 --> 10:09.821
Yeah, annoying, boring sometimes.

10:10.823 --> 10:15.890
But a key point in the spiritual life, everybody, is you're not in control.

10:16.610 --> 10:18.833
We put a high premium on control.

10:19.073 --> 10:22.577
I love being in control of things, right?

10:22.597 --> 10:24.179
Nothing wrong with that in itself.

10:24.760 --> 10:29.105
But when it comes to the deepest things in life, you're not in control.

10:30.827 --> 10:31.648
God's in control.

10:32.809 --> 10:43.922
And can you learn to live out of that acceptance, to let go of your need to manipulate everything and let God set the tone

10:44.642 --> 10:50.669
You know, I told you before about these insights from the initiation rituals of primal peoples.

10:51.370 --> 10:59.239
And one of these insights I've taken as a basic truth in the spiritual life, which is your life is not about you.

11:01.361 --> 11:02.122
It's your life.

11:03.243 --> 11:05.806
And you have to live it, but it's not about you.

11:06.987 --> 11:08.749
It's not about what you envision.

11:09.590 --> 11:10.772
It's about what God wants.

11:11.893 --> 11:12.754
And that means

11:13.378 --> 11:15.221
We sometimes have to wait.

11:17.184 --> 11:18.205
Decenter the ego.

11:19.026 --> 11:20.709
Let God do what he wants to do.

11:21.510 --> 11:23.493
Think you're the prophet Jonah, right?

11:23.513 --> 11:26.097
Jonah hears God's voice, but no, no, I'm not doing that.

11:26.277 --> 11:31.505
And in control of his life, he goes as far away as possible, gets on the boat.

11:31.625 --> 11:34.169
I am gonna sail away from what God wants.

11:35.351 --> 11:36.112
What's God do?

11:36.152 --> 11:39.317
He sends the great fish to swallow up Jonah.

11:39.658 --> 11:42.642
And then watch how he has to wait.

11:43.266 --> 11:54.500
It's one of the great prayers in the Bible, by the way, when Jonah prays from the depths and from the belly of the fish, the day profundus from these deep down places where he's made to wait.

11:55.161 --> 11:56.162
But here's interesting.

11:56.523 --> 12:03.331
What's happening while he's waiting is he's being brought by God, exactly where God wants him to be.

12:04.873 --> 12:07.316
What's waiting, just dumb suffering?

12:07.497 --> 12:09.239
No, no, no, not if you see with the eyes of faith.

12:10.641 --> 12:11.762
Waiting is

12:12.930 --> 12:19.000
turning one's life, sometimes painfully, over to the purposes of God.

12:20.502 --> 12:27.273
Accepting not my timetable, God's timetable, which is always right.

12:28.475 --> 12:34.284
Not the life I would lead of my own volition, but the life that God wants me to lead.

12:35.166 --> 12:37.069
That involves waiting.

12:38.030 --> 12:40.434
I've talked to my brother, priests, about this a lot.

12:40.706 --> 12:44.010
the various promises we take and everyone focuses on celibacy.

12:44.030 --> 12:51.177
But the one that I think is maybe most spiritually difficult and life-giving is obedience.

12:52.038 --> 12:58.706
When you make a promise of obedience, I remember putting my hands in the hands of Joseph Bernadine many years ago when I was ordained a priest.

12:59.406 --> 13:03.571
And I said, I promise obedience to you and your successors.

13:04.572 --> 13:06.514
You know, barely knowing what I was

13:07.298 --> 13:10.962
I mean, I knew what I was promising, but I mean, I didn't know the contours of it at all.

13:13.125 --> 13:14.346
What will he want me to do?

13:14.386 --> 13:15.968
What will his successors want me to do?

13:17.650 --> 13:19.713
Eventually, what will the successor of Peter want me to do?

13:20.974 --> 13:29.204
I didn't know, but I was surrendering my career at that point, my projects, my plans.

13:29.805 --> 13:34.450
And I was saying, I'm willing to wait to see what God wants me to do.

13:35.362 --> 13:37.705
It happens a lot to priests and bishops too.

13:37.765 --> 13:40.267
It's like, okay, you know, you have as a teacher at Mundalein.

13:40.287 --> 13:41.429
Well, what's next for you?

13:42.230 --> 13:43.491
I don't know.

13:43.511 --> 13:44.913
I was made rector of the seminary.

13:45.013 --> 13:45.693
Oh, well, you're rector.

13:45.713 --> 13:46.895
You know, rectors often become bishops.

13:46.915 --> 13:47.976
When are you becoming a bishop?

13:48.597 --> 13:48.937
I don't know.

13:49.858 --> 13:52.541
I become an auxiliary bishop in Los Angeles of all places.

13:52.601 --> 13:53.001
Who knew?

13:53.122 --> 13:54.303
I had no expectation of that.

13:55.184 --> 13:56.145
Hey, well, you're auxiliary.

13:56.165 --> 13:57.887
When do you become bishop of your own diocese?

13:57.907 --> 13:58.367
I don't know.

13:58.407 --> 14:01.431
And now here I am, bishop of my own diocese.

14:01.451 --> 14:02.272
Oh, what's next for you?

14:02.812 --> 14:04.434
I don't know.

14:04.546 --> 14:07.749
I want to say, because I made this gesture a long time ago.

14:07.809 --> 14:16.138
I put my hands in the hands of somebody else, and I do what I'm told to do, and I wait to see what God's up to.

14:16.499 --> 14:20.964
Can I leave you with one more image from the Bible, and it's to prepare us for Christmas?

14:22.325 --> 14:25.929
Think of during Advent, what were the magi doing?

14:26.770 --> 14:30.314
Well, during Advent, the magi were looking.

14:30.334 --> 14:32.476
They were watching.

14:32.516 --> 14:34.418
They were waiting.

14:35.042 --> 14:39.929
for a sign that they weren't going to go where they wanted to go.

14:39.949 --> 14:43.975
They were patiently waiting for an indication.

14:44.636 --> 14:48.602
But listen, when they got it, they moved.

14:49.023 --> 14:51.346
See, there's nothing passive about what I'm describing.

14:51.927 --> 14:55.733
When you wait, you're letting go, that's painful.

14:55.813 --> 14:59.578
I know you're letting go of your ego, but you're turning your life over to God.

14:59.739 --> 15:02.002
And when you get the indication from God,

15:02.882 --> 15:05.167
You go, you act, you move.

15:06.108 --> 15:09.315
I think that's the spiritual attitude of Advent.

15:09.756 --> 15:10.357
And God bless you.

15:15.668 --> 15:19.275
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

15:19.656 --> 15:24.786
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

